<h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
column2: \">Since December 2005, the Women Alive Program is committed

column1: to women living on the streets. We provide an emergency overnight shelter and
hospitality center, where homeless women can have dinner, take showers, do
laundry, take a deep breath from the life in the streets and spend the night in
a safe, non-judgmental and nurturing space. This is the only no-questions-asked

emergency walk-in shelter for street women in Monterey County.

The Women Alive! Program is located in Dorothy's Place Hospitality Center, in
the Dayroom area. Every day, our Dayroom closes at 2:00 p.m. for cleaning and
transformation into the Women Alive! Shelter. Homeless women may enter from
7:00-8:30 every night and stay until 6:30 in the morning. <span><h4>
<h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><strong><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
love and peace, this emergency shelter not only seeks to provide a safe roof to
homeless women but also to validate their human and loving capacity to engage
in constructive attitudes.<span>&nbsp
to offer them some stabilization based on companionship and gentleness.<span><h4>
<h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
column2: \">The women who come to this shelter have many

column1: opportunities to share meals, safe sleeping space and engage in conversations
that support their dreams and efforts to move forward with their lives!&nbsp
We can say that the real gift of the shelter<span>&nbsp
column2: <span>is the daily re-discovery of life and opportunities.<span><h4>

column1: <h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
column2: \">We understand that being homeless is first a

column1: reality of aloneness and soul hunger.<span>&nbsp
column3: s a blessing to witness distraught women receive the

column1: chance for a safe deep breath
column2: how a smile slowly come to their faces, along

column1: with the slow dawning realization that they are no longer alone. <span><h4>
<h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
column2: \">Because of that, we provide homeless women with a

column1: space where they can cultivate nurturing feelings and sense of well-being.&nbsp
We constantly seek for new and better ways to communicate, to deeply listen and
help them to face daily challenges, including supplanting demoralizations due
to their impaired conditions. <span>&nbsp
our doors for women at night constantly amaze us. We have discovered that being
&lsquo
column3: not only feels really good but it&rsquo
column4: s constructive and

column1: self-developing! <span><h4>

<h4 class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia
column2: \">You can help keeping the Women Alive! shelter open

citizens from the Salinas community as well as from grants from United Way

Trust. <span>&nbsp
column2:

column1: Bureau of Land Management (BLM) Hollister Resource Area,1,"20 Hamilton Ct","NULL","Hollister",95023,"The federal government has set aside roughly 15,000 acres of Fort Ord¿s undeveloped back country for management by the BLM to protect rare species and other natural habitats. Most of this land is located between the developed part of Fort Ord and Highway 68 and includes oak woodlands, dense chaparral shrublands, rolling grassy hills, wetlands, and ponds. The BLM habitat area will provide homes for 35 species of rare plants and animals, including small annual flowers, unique chaparral shrubs, black legless lizards, tiger salamanders, ornate shrews, blue butterflies, and tiny fairy shrimp. The BLM coordinates the development of a detailed management plan (CRMP) that will guide management of all the natural habitats at Fort Ord. CSUMB, UC Santa Cruz, Monterey County, California State Parks, and local cities as well as other public and nonprofit agencies and organizations will also be involved in the development and implementation of the management plan. Additionally, uniformed BLM staff, including law enforcement rangers, patrol the lands to enhance public enjoyment of the land and to assure that natural resources and public safety are protected.    ","NULL","NULL","NULL","Education|Environment","Government","Service Learning"

Chartwell School,0,"1490 Imperial St.","NULL","Seaside",93955,"Since 1983, Chartwell School has been educating students with a wide range of visual and auditory language-based learning challenges in a way that provides the skills, confidence, and creativity to return successfully to mainstream education and enjoy learning throughout life.  The typical student enters Chartwell with academic performance two or more years below expected grade level, despite normal or better intelligence.  Here, what others see as problems, Chartwell sees as opportunities.  Our immediate goal is to guide children toward becoming healthy, curious, confident and appreciated learners again. ",100,"Test results from 1999-present reveal that students gain more than one full year in key basic skills in reading, writing, vocabulary, comprehension, and math for each year they are at Chartwell.  Many gain even more.  After an average of three years at Chartwell, students return to mainstream education as capable learners.  More than 75% of our students return to public schools. Chartwell estimates that more than 90% complete high school and 70% go on to college or other post-secondary learning.  These results are much higher than would ever have been predicted for this type of learner without successful intervention at Chartwell.

The roles of illiteracy and learning failure in juvenile crime, teen pregnancy, high school dropouts, childhood anxiety and depression, substance abuse, long-term welfare dependence, and adult incarceration are well documented.  Chartwell is determined to make a difference in these statistics. Chartwell  alumni often tell us, ¿You changed my life.¿

A capstone project could include developing and conducting an alumni survey via mail and email to further document the effectiveness of Chartwell's programs.","http://www.chartwell.org","Advocacy|Education|Literacy","Non-Profit|Elementary School","Service Learning"

Martin Luther King Jr. Academy is a public school serving grades 3,4,5,6,7 and 8 within the Seaside community. The Under the Big Top After School Program is designed to serve the physical, emotional, intellectual and social needs of young adolescents.

Students at this stage of life demonstrate a significant diversity in rates of growth and maturity.  Most students between the ages of 11 and 14 are undergoing the following changes - social maturation, growth in independence, growth in importance of peer relationships, intellectual maturation, and development of norms and values.

These physical, intellectual, emotional and social changes do not always occur easily or smoothly.  Early adolescence has traditionally been a time of difficulty.  For this reason, it has been suggested that students in this age range be educated in an environment that addresses and eases the transition from childhood to full adolescence.  The goal of the Under the Big Top After School Program is to provide a safe and nurturing environment where students are active learners in academic and enrichment opportunity classes.
Program Schedule:
3:30-4:25  Academic Support Class
4:25-4:45  Snack (provided by program)
4:45-5:45  Enrichment Club
5:45-6:00  Bus pick-up and student departure
How our program works:

Each student is enrolled in an Academic Support class for the first hour of the program from 3:30-4:25.  Tutors help students finish their homework and check for comprehension and accuracy.  Students who are finished with homework have the opportunity to work on one of our hands on activities focusing on Math, Science, Language Arts and Social Studies concepts & skills.  This gives students a chance to apply what they have learned during the school day.

Enrichment Clubs are held during the second hour of the program from 4:45-5:45.  Each month, students are able to enroll in the Enrichment Club of their choice.  We offer 4-5 different Clubs per month-long \"Session\".  Examples of Clubs we have offered are: Drama, Art, Cooking, Computers, Sports, Gardening, Science, Oceanography, Singing, Dancing, Music, Girls Club, Newspaper writing, Film making, Student Leadership Committee and much, much more!  Enrichment Clubs are a reward for students and an opportunity for them to learn life skills and develop personal interests.

Our goal is to make learning fun and relevant to the lives of our students. We do this by turning academic concepts into hands-on activities. With the decrease in the variety of elective classes offered during the school day, our program tries to fill in those gaps and balance academics with enrichment opportunities.

Museum of Monterey (formerly Monterey History and Maritime Museum),1,"5 Custom House Plaza","NULL","Monterey",93940,"

The Museum of Monterey is dedicated to being a leader
in models of history and social studies education and a regional leader
in educational programming. Therefore, the Museum will implement an
array of education-centered programs including outreach, and special
events. Programs will engage the community in innovative and dynamic
ways while providing opportunities for life-long learning.  To support
these goals, the Museum is committed to the creation of a strong
educational program with an infrastructure that supports effective
services. We intend to increase the potential for visual and historic
literacy, creativity, and critical thinking skills. Topically, the Museum of Monterey will focus on the Monterey Bay as a
community tied to the land and inspire the appreciation for the beauty

and complexity of its rich history.

University of California Cooperative Extension UCCE,1,"1432 Abbott St.","NULL","Salinas",93901,"UCCE conducts research and provides education at the county level- in agriculture, the environment, community nutrition and youth development.   As regards agriculture, specifically plant pathology, UCCE  uses careful field assessments and thorough lab analyses to assist growers in reducing pesticide use and crop loss.As regards nutrition: The Family Nutrition Education Program provides free curriculum to schools, trains volunteers to provide nutrition education to community members, and participates in projects that improve health literacy and help youth develop good nutrition and fitness habits. Funded by the Food Stamp Program which also helps participants to purchase nutritious foods for better diet, Family Nutrition Education offers menus, recipes, nutrition classes, newsletters, fotonovelas, hand-outs, and access to a library of videos, books and display items with a nutrition theme. As regards youth development: UCCE's program develops programs for youth in science, technology, environmental stewardship and natural resource education in Santa Cruz and Monterey Counties and serves as an educational resource by developing and disseminating science, technology, environmental stewardship and natural resource education information relevant and useful to youth, associated organizations, and agencies.","NULL","Innovations in student-generated learning materials to improve nutrition literacy of local residents are possible.","NULL","Agriculture|Education|Environment|Health & Human Services|Youth Development","College/University","Service Learning"

Girl Scouts of Monterey Bay,0,"10550 Merritt Street","NULL","Castroville","95012-3311","

Girl Scouts of Monterey Bay is committed to helping today's girls become tomorrow's leaders. The Girl Scout program is girl-driven, reflecting the ever-changing needs and interests of participating girls.

Our membership is as diverse as the area we serve: more than 5,400 girls and over 2,500 adult volunteers from Monterey, Santa Cruz and San Benito counties. As part of the Girl Scouts of the USA and Girl Scouts of Monterey Bay commitment to diversity, Girl Scouting offers opportunities for girls to learn more about other cultures and communities, to build skills in understanding and to broaden their outlook.

California Rural Legal Assistance (CRLA),1,"3 Williams Road","NULL","Salinas",93905,"

California Rural Legal Assistance, Inc. (CRLA) provides free legal assistance to low-income people in twenty-one California communities, including Monterey, Salinas, Watsonville, Gilroy and Santa Cruz. Our organization was founded over 40 years ago to provide legal services to farm workers. Since then we have expanded our work. We currently assist farm workers and other low-income persons in these five priority areas: 1) Labor and employment, 2) Housing, 3) Education, 4) Civil rights, and 5)

Family security, such as public benefits.

We are a fairly small school with approximately 400 students in grades K-5. Our students come from diverse cultural backgrounds and often speak English as their second language. We celebrate this diversity. You will find our school has a very welcoming feel to it. The staff is friendly and the students are generally very polite and respectful. We encourage people to volunteer who are conscientious, caring, and enjoy being around children.
